feedback: I noticed that single features tended to belong to one family or the other more often and double or triple features seemed to go to the other family.
I tried to look for patterns, though do not know if I was that successful. It was tricky! Overall, it seemed that one "Family" was more likely to have 3 features than the other.

The left side (1) seemed to have more circles present and the right side (2) seemed to have less. So following this pattern I said (2) for any where only one circle appeared and (1) for any where more than one circle appeared.
Honestly they looked the same so I guessed.
I had no other strategy other then trying to recall which combination appeared most in what family.

I tried to find patterns, like in the first test, it seemed that the face that had all features was frequently from family 2. I remembered that each family had about equal numbers, so I tried to keep track of how often I was pressing 1 or 2 to equally divide the families.
In the second session, I noticed that most of the boxes that only had one circle were from the second family.
I couldn't find a pattern
I noticed on the second set most in family one were on the opposite side of the box.

I noticed that each trial seemed to have one combination of features that overwhelmingly favored a particular side, with the third combination of features being relatively evenly distributed. For example, in the second trial, every single example image with 3 circles favored family 1. Therefore, I virtually always selected 1 when I saw 3 circles, only selecting 2 once or twice due to the instruction that both families have all possible combinations.
i watched the families for a while and then made some guesses as to what trait was dominant for what family
i tried to memorize the patterns during the practice rounds
Look for early patterns then just watch for confirmations of the code. Appears to be based on number of objects pictured

I noticed the nose and mouth showed up more for the left and eyes for the right. Then I noticed pair of circle or all three showed up more for the left and singular or two circles but far apart showed up more for the right.
tried the best to remember what I could
images that only had 1 feature usually were of one family while images that had 2 or 3 features were usually of another family
